# AST/IR nodes are frozen classes — construct them, don't hand-roll frozen object literals

Every node in an AST/IR hierarchy in this repo is a **frozen class** (abstract base → concrete subclasses, `Object.freeze(this)` in the constructor, visitor dispatch via `accept`). The pattern and its rationale live in the `ast-visitor-pattern` skill. This rule is the always-on guardrail for the one failure mode that keeps slipping through review: a **contract-free factory (or test) that returns `Object.freeze({ kind: '…', … })` plain objects** for something that is part of an AST/IR alphabet.

If a value is (or belongs in the fields of) an AST/IR node, it must be a class instance:

- A factory like `lit()`, `fn()`, `col()`, `createTable()` returns a **`new SomeNode(…)`**, not `Object.freeze({ … })`.
- A node's child fields (a column's `default`, a clause's operands) hold **subclass instances**, not `{ kind, … }` literals.
- Tests construct nodes with `new SubclassNode(…)` (or the contract-free factory), **never** `{ kind: '…', … }` literals — see the skill's "In tests" section.

## Why a frozen object literal is not good enough

- **No identity.** `instanceof` fails, `accept()` doesn't exist, and a downstream `freezeColumns`-style shallow-copy (`{ ...node }`) silently strips the prototype — turning a typed node back into an anonymous bag. Classes survive copying and freezing intact.
- **No exhaustiveness.** The whole point of the class/visitor pattern is that adding a variant is a compile error at every dispatch site. A `{ kind }` literal route bypasses the visitor and re-opens the silent-omission hole the pattern closed.
- **Construction-time invariants get skipped.** Validation that belongs in the constructor (e.g. `lit()` rejecting a non-literal value) can't run if callers fabricate the object directly.

## What stays a plain union (not every `{ kind }` is in scope)

This rule targets **AST/IR alphabets that have a visitor / multiple dispatch sites**. A foundational, widely-consumed discriminated union with a single classifier (e.g. the foundational `ColumnDefault` in `@prisma-next/contract`) is deliberately a plain union — promoting it would have a large blast radius and it has no visitor. When a surface needs the class shape but the foundational union must stay a plain union, introduce a **local class hierarchy on that surface** (mirror the foundational union's values) rather than mutating the foundational type.

## Quick check before staging

```bash
git diff --cached -- '*.ts' | rg '^\+' | rg "Object\.freeze\(\{\s*kind:"
```

A hit on an AST/IR construction surface means you're hand-rolling a frozen object literal where a `new …Node(…)` belongs. Rewrite it as a class instance. (`as const` literals and foundational-union builders that legitimately stay plain are the only exceptions — confirm the target type has no visitor before waving one through.)
